## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Tech stack: React (with hooks), TypeScript, and a state management approach (React Context or lightweight Redux) as appropriate.
- Routing: /content-dashboard as main route; /content-dashboard/editor for Content Editor integration.
- Data fetching: Custom hooks for fetching panels’ data; ensure null checks and typed responses.
- Components must be accessible (aria-labels, semantic HTML, keyboard navigation).
- State safety: All arrays initialized to [] via useState([]).
- Drag-and-drop: Implement using a robust library (e.g., React DnD or HTML5 Drag with proper guards).
- Form controls: Inputs, selects, chips with focus states and accessible labels.
- UI consistency: Use the provided design system tokens for colors, typography, spacing, borders, and shadows.
- Performance: Lazy load heavy widgets (e.g., SEO charts) and memoize expensive subtrees.
- Testing: Unit tests for critical hooks and UI logic; integration tests for drag-to-reschedule and end-to-end flows (where feasible).

### Backend
- Data access layer should expose endpoints for:
  - GET /content/items with pagination and filters
  - GET /content/item/{id} for detail
  - POST /content/item with creation payload
  - PUT /content/item/{id} for updates (stage transitions, scheduling, etc.)
  - GET /cronjobs, POST /cronjobs, PUT /cronjobs for content automation
  - GET /analytics/seo, /analytics/performance for SEO data
  - GET /audits/run/{id} for audit trails
  - GET /agents/recommendations for topic suggestions
- Data models (schemas) must reflect the project context:
  - ContentItem: id, title, slug, projectId, status (idea/research/draft/edit/publish), authorId, assigneeIds, calendarItem, scheduledAt, publishedAt, seoKeywords, performanceMetrics, version, createdAt, updatedAt
  - CronJob: id, name, enabled, scheduleCron, timezone, triggerType, targetAgentId, inputPayload, permissions, constraints, safetyRails, retryPolicy, outputs
  - RunArtifact: id, cronJobId, status, startedAt, finishedAt, artifacts, logs, diffs
  - SEOInsight: id, contentItemId, keyword, searchVolume, difficulty, suggestedTitle, metaDescription
  - AgentRecommendation: id, topic, rationale, confidence
- Safety and validation: All endpoints return data shaped as per response validators; guard against nulls; ensure id fields are validated.

### Integration
- Data flow:
  - ContentDashboard pulls data from:
    - Content module (items, stages, scheduling)
    - Cronjobs module (content automation runs)
    - SEO/Performance analytics module
    - Agent recommendations module
  - Actions trigger:
    - Stage transitions update content items and enqueue events to the automation layer
    - Drag-and-drop on ContentCalendarPanel triggers scheduling updates via CronJobs
    - Publishing actions invoke publishing connectors (via the Content Pipeline Automation features), scheduling jobs, and recording run artifacts
- Consistency:
  - All state mutations should be auditable; write actions should emit run artifacts and logs
  - Use a single source of truth for content items; propagate updates to all panels
- Error handling:
  - Centralized error boundaries; show user-friendly error messages with retry options
  - Maintain UI disabled states when critical data is loading or errors exist

---

## User Experience Flow

1. User opens Content Dashboard ("/content-dashboard").
2. Overview tiles render:
   - Content Calendar shows upcoming scheduled posts; drag a post to reschedule and confirm the new time; behind the scenes, a cronjob update is created and run history updated.
   - Drafts Panel displays ideas to publish-ready drafts; user advances a piece to the next stage, assigns editors, or requests approvals.
   - Publishing Queue shows imminent publishes with statuses and next steps; user can retry failed items or cancel upcoming publishes.
   - Agent Recommendations provides topic/story ideas with rationale and confidence; user can push ideas into the Editor with one click.
   - SEO/Performance Widgets present keyword suggestions and traffic projections; user can click to open the Editor with the item loaded.
3. User uses Global Search to locate content, projects, cronjobs, runs, or users; filters refine the results.
4. User clicks Content Editor shortcut to open the end-to-end editor for a selected item or a new idea; editor supports idea→research→draft→edit→schedule→publish with versioning and collaboration features.
5. User reviews audit trails and run artifacts for actions taken, including reversion options if needed.

